So we need to prove that `T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1)) = 0` `őĹ.restrict G`-almost everywhere given `őľ F = 0`.

Let's continue with the proof.

We need to show `eLpNorm (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) = 0`.

From `hT F G hF hG` we get `AESTronglyMeasurable (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) őĹ ‚ąß eLpNorm (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) ‚Č§ c * (őľ F) ^ p‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal * (őĹ G) ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal`.

So we have the inequality `eLpNorm (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) ‚Č§ c * (őľ F) ^ p‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal * (őĹ G) ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal`.

Since `őľ F = 0`, the right-hand side is `c * 0 ^ p‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal * (őĹ G) ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal`. Since `p ‚Č† 0` and `p ‚Č† ‚ä§`, `p‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal` is positive, so `0 ^ p‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal = 0`. Therefore, the right-hand side is `c * 0 * (őĹ G) ^ p'‚ĀĽ¬Ļ.toReal = 0`.

Therefore, we have `eLpNorm (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) ‚Č§ 0`. Since the norm is non-negative, this means `eLpNorm (T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1))) 1 (őĹ.restrict G) = 0`.

And `eLpNorm f 1 őľ = 0` if and only if `f = 0` `őľ`-almost everywhere. So `T (F.indicator (fun _ ‚Ü¶ 1)) = 0` `őĹ.restrict G`-almost everywhere, which is what we need.

